metadata.name: BAI #199
metadata.description:
The first blueprint was found in 1947 on the northwestern shore of the Dead Sea.
It has been studied several times.
Numerous theories arose trying to explain its origin.
None of them was decided conclusively.

One year ago, a rare group of waves coming from space was intercepted on earth.
This happened during the 2021 summer.
It was unclear if they were born from natural events.
Dying stars, black holes... Humans tried to find patterns. Find a meaning for them.
None of the analyses made any sense.

Bai was a young physicist and Ph.D. student.
Her mother was a civil engineer working in finance.
Her father was an architect and a generative artist.
She had a personal interest in linguistics and algorithmic art, influenced by her father.
She was the one who managed to decrypt the information using her own algorithms.

Those frequencies were the gate to sets of technical drawings, matching precisely the physical blueprint found in 1947.

It's been a year since the waves were discovered.
No definite conclusions have been made yet regarding their origin or their meaning.
Nevertheless, the number of theories keeps increasing with every new blueprint decrypted.

The frequencies keep passing by the earth.
There is still so much investigation to be carried out.
So many questions to be answered.
Yet, the financial crisis is making the budget for investigation decrease rapidly.
The Institute of Space Sciences is running an initiative to self-fund this project.
Three hundred thirteen open spots can then seize those waves.
Encapsulating them as NFTs.


â€”--------------------

This project is an attempt to experiment with two main ideas arising from technical plans:

1. The inner beauty of architectural plans, city plans, industrial blueprints, and any other type of documents of that nature. A study of graphic elements like annotations, dashed lines, grids, etc. disposed of in different manners to create aesthetically appealing compositions.

2. How does the viewer analyze and interpret abstract compositions of technical plans? Triggering different thoughts and ideas: A Rorschach test with blueprints instead of ink blots.

â€”--------------------

All the minters at the first tear of the dutch auction will be able to claim A or B: A being one HD signed print of their blueprint or B their unique 1/1, on top of the NFT minted.

Those unique 1/1s will be pre-curated outputs from this algorithm. Some of the 1/1 parameters could be chosen by the minter: colors, main composition, shapes, density, name of the blueprint... so that the result will be a collaboration between the minter, Ismahelio, and the algorithm itself.

Minters at the second tier of the dutch auction can claim one unique 1/1. The difference with the first tier is that the minter won't be involved in the design process. The piece will be designed and curated by Ismahelio.

If there are any of these 1/1s to be claimed. They will be minted within an Objkt.com collection and airdropped to the minters.

â€”--------------------
Heavily dense compositions might not load on some mobile devices with insufficient memory.
The quality of the piece on phones and tablets has been decreased programmatically.
Visualize the piece in a powerful enough computer for the best experience.

Click 1: Activate
Click 2: increase speed
1: save 4000x4000 png
2: save 6000x6000 png
3: save 8000x8000 png

Original piece by Ismahelio.
August 2022. Madrid - Cadiz. Spain.
Made with p5.js

metadata.name: Junkspace #48
metadata.description:
You never notice, it is passthrough. It is familiar but unfamiliar. It is everywhere and nowhere at the same time. It can contain anything, but it doesn't. Being here is lonely, even surrounded. It is the debris of modern architecture. It is the uncanny valley of the places. It is the Junkspace.

Junkspace is an algorithm inspired by the well-known namesake article of Rem Koolhaas (October, Vol. 100, Obsolescence. (Spring, 2002), pp. 175-190). The work is a generative approach to visualize it in the plan view. There are several paper types, partitions, floorings, and color palettes to achieve the residue of modernization.

This work exists thanks to the p5js library. To give some back to the community, you will contribute to the Processing Foundation by collecting this work.

Press "s" to save the image.

metadata.name: In the Edge #426
metadata.description:
./ In the Edge

It's been a long time since your journey began, caring for the ones you love, pursuing your dreams, and giving the best of you. 

Now you know you can't go back, you can't go further, you know your time is coming.

How far did you go? It doesn't matter, you did it right. Your accomplishments will serve well the next generations in their journeys, in their search for themselves.

Now it's time to stop, time to take a moment and contemplate the vast universe.

Soon all of this will be ending.

You did it right.

Embrace the void.
=========
=========


./ Color scheme (feature)
There are 12 color schemes and with each set, specific arrays for color collections for the space, stars, planet, and accent colors. 

These are color schemes in the known universe of "In the Edge":
- Mars visions
- Cyberpunk
- Unknown passenger 
- Renegade
- Primary
- Coral
- r.e.d.
- Machines of an ancient-future 
- The void
- Tinted light 
- Malibu dreams
- Atari (horrendous brown, red and yellowish combinations... I love it)

./ Mountain type (feature)
In the Edge, you will find a mountain, and that mountain will be special, which type will you find?

- Parallela insolitum
- Sandy dunes of the truth
- Wavy uncertainty
- Intrinsic soul ridges
- Cerritulus formationis

./ Mountain direction (feature)
Life is about direction... mountains too.

- Left
- Right
- Left-Right

./ Space scenery
This is the spicy touch, some of the iterations will have animation and others will not, giving you a clear view of the magnificent space in front of you.

- Clean (NOT animated)
- Windy planet (animated)
- Topographic planet (animated)
- Meteor shower (animated)

./ Distance from Earth (feature)
How far did you go? Your travel could be from 1 lightyear to 999,999,999 lightyears (that's a lot of lights and years!). However just a few will pass the barrier of 99,999,999ly.

// Additional perks
./ Planet names 
Planet names are unique and they are conformed by three blocks.

The first block is a conjunction between ancient Latin names and Japanese last names. 

The second block takes the last three characters from the fxhash.

The third block takes three numbers from the number seed obtained from fxrand().

The planet you land will be unique, as unique as you are.

// Controls
./ Pause-Play animation
Because maybe (and just maybe) you want to freeze the perfect moment before closing your eyes.

[Backspace] Pause.
[Enter] Play

Applies to "Space scenery" features windy planet, topographic planet, and meteor shower.

metadata.name: Elemental walks II #54
metadata.description:
"Elemental walks II" is an extended exploration of the interaction and perception of different systems. The generated double grid pattern, the first system, transforms into a crowd of random walkers, this second system moves in random but constrained ways, and with each movement a third system is generated: the texture.

Use the 1, 2, 3, 4, 5 keys to switch between 5 states of movement within the dynamic pattern, you can pause ('p'), speed up ('+') or slow down ('-') the movement. 

Click on the canvas and the colours change within the composition.

'r' to reset position or release the walkers
'p' to toggle pause/play

'1' for vertical movement
'2' for diagonal movement
'3' for horizontal movement
'4' for a second diagonal movement
'5' for vertical and horizontal movement

'-' to slow down
'+' for faster movement

's' save png
'j' save jpg

metadata.name: Alleles #316
metadata.description:
An allele, short for 'allelomorph', is an alternative version of a specific gene.

This collection (which is in no way scientifically accurate), was born out of an exercise in simplicity. Outputs are made up of arrangements of squares in various compositions, yet within that we are free to imagine what they could mean. For some, the resulting shapes might represent DNA strands or atoms. Others might see cells or the building blocks of the hereditary instructions that shape us as individuals. 

A generative genetic report accompanies each output to spark the imagination and attempt to attach further meaning to each composition. Some gene sequences carry mutations, however not all mutations are visually apparent. Please refer to the fxhash features to view the reports accordingly.

Texture is used subtly, so for maximum enjoyment it is recommended that you save and view your outputs at full size in order to best enjoy the details.

Press 'S' to save a 2400 x 3396 px PNG file.

attributes.name: Genetic Profile
attributes.value: Initial analysis of available data indicates that suggests subject may suffer from frequent bouts of emotional outbursts and [REDACTED], yet also has the ability to show unrivaled intelligence and foresight. Maximum potential hereditary height (excluding nutritional and environmental factors) is estimated at 129-134cm. Projected natural lifespan estimated at 87-87 years. Additional presence of mutated markers would benefit from re-examination to asses the viability of the subject as a candidate for programs for the enhanced. Closer examination of mutated markers 906 through 1144, as these may indicate the presence of atmokinesis and or synaptic entanglement (telepathic) abilities.

metadata.name: Moonlit Mountains #46
metadata.description:
In this work I tried to depict variations of a forested mountain landscape lit by moonlight. The trees, mountains, sky, clouds, moon, stars, everything is generated 100% with code using random numbers from various distributions.

There are many features that are randomly chosen and used to guide the composition. The values for each feature are not equally probable. Some rare features are a Blue Moon (5%) and Shooting Star (15%).

Features:

Steepness: 1 -> 10 (larger values are steeper)

Big Trees: 0 -> 3  (large trees in foreground)

Tree Density: Low, Medium, High

Moon Phase: New, Waning Crescent, Waning Quarter, Full, Waxing Quarter, Waxing Crescent

Moon Size: Small, Medium, Large, Very Large

Fog Level: Low, Medium, High, Very High

Cloud Level: None, Low, Medium, High, Very High

Stars: None, Low, Medium, High, Very High

Prevailing Winds: Leftward, Neutral, Rightward

Moon Color: Blue, Red, Orange, Yellow, Silver

Shooting Star: true, false

Sky Color: many

metadata.name: Puzzles of the mind #109
metadata.description:
This is abstract art based on mathematical structure.
The puzzle of your mind seems broken and rearranged.

Mode has 2 variations.
 - Normal
 - Black
Color has 3 variations.
 - å¸¸ç£-tokiwa- (Green)
 - çœŸæœ±-shinshu- (Red)
 - ç´ºç¢§-konpeki- (Blue)
Color Level has 2 variations.
 - High
 - Low
Square Size has 3 variations.
 - Small
 - Middle
 - Large

Tokiwa is a Japanese word meaning always the same. It's green like the color of evergreen leaves.

Shinshu is a Japanese word that refers to a dull red color like vermilion. It means vermilion in its natural state with nothing mixed in.

Konpeki is a Japanese word that describes a deep blue, very close to azure. It's like a clear sky with summer sunshine.

metadata.name: Exotic Quarpets #3
metadata.description:
Exotic Quarpets began as an entry to Raphaelle de Courville's weekly creative coding challenge, with the topic being 'Quilts'. Taking inspiration from the Persian rugs that we would roll out at home every winter, I tried to create an aesthetic reminiscent of those with a gen-art touch.

  The generated images, depending on the aspect ratio that you get, are quite large at roughly 4kx4k pixels. Generating these images can take a few seconds depending on your device, so please be patient. Save the high rez image by pressing the S key on your keyboard, I recommend zooming in and having a look at all the details!

  For an optimal viewing experience please run the token in a modern desktop browser!
